- "Shining stars" refers to teams with a high number of top-performing athletes;
- "Leading the pack" means having the most top-performing athletes;
- "Top-performing athletes" are those who have earned more than 100 points in confirmed events.

- "Top-performing athletes" refers to athletes who are ranked in the top three positions in each race;
- "World Cup events" are a specific type of event in the database;
- "Average points" are calculated from the points of all athletes in the top three positions across all races in World Cup events.

- "shining stars" refers to the athletes;
- "grand arena of competition" represents the context of sports events;
- "accomplishments" include the total points earned and the ranking within each event.

- "Winning an event" refers to ranking 1st in the event;
- "More than one event" implies the athlete has won at least two events;
- "Events and disciplines" are specific competitions within a particular skiing discipline.

- 'stand tall and strong' refers to being in the top 5 in height and weight within their skiing discipline;
- 'shine brightly in the races' refers to being in the top 5 in competition rank for Slalom and Giant Slalom disciplines;
- 'achieving both physical and competitive greatness' means meeting both physical and performance criteria.

- "shining star" refers to the top-performing athlete;
- "lights up the snow with the brilliance of their points" refers to the highest total points earned;
- "leaving all others in the shadow of their trail" refers to outperforming other athletes.
